2.c. Correlational analysis on the dataset

In[427]:
numerical_features = dataset.select_dtypes(include=["number"])

# Plot correlation heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(numerical_features.corr(), annot=True, fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap of Numerical Features")
plt.show()

Impact on feature selection:

  • As seen in the heatmap, most features have very low correlation with "Is Fraudulent" variable. However, low correlation does not always mean a feature is useless Some features might have a non-linear relationship with fraud, which correlation analysis cannot detect.
  • If two independent features are highly correlated, we can drop one of them to avoid redundancy.
  • But the correlations among independent features are also weak, so we dont have major multicollinearity concerns here.
  • Correlation only captures linear relationships. Fraud detection can be complex and nonlinear, requiring techniques beyond correlation analysis.

# Handling Outliers using IQR method
numerical_features = dataset.select_dtypes(include=["number"])

Q1 = numerical_features.quantile(0.25)
Q3 = numerical_features.quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
outliers = ((numerical_features < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) | (numerical_features > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR))).sum()
print("Outliers Count:\n", outliers)

Handle Class Imbalance using SMOTE technique

Applying Logistic regression with 80, 20 ratio train and test data and also with 70, 30 ratio

In[451]:
from sklearn.datasets import make_classification
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

# Generate an imbalanced dataset
x, y = make_classification(n_classes=2, class_sep=2, weights=[0.95, 0.05],
                           n_samples=1000, random_state=42)

# Check class distribution before SMOTE
print("Before SMOTE:", dict(pd.Series(y).value_counts()))

# Split data into training and test sets with 80, 20 ratio
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42)

# 70, 30 ratio of training and test sets
x_train_70, x_test_30, y_train_70, y_test_30 = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=42)

# Apply SMOTE on the training set
smote = SMOTE(sampling_strategy='auto', random_state=42)
x_train, y_train = smote.fit_resample(x_train, y_train)
x_train_70, y_train_70 = smote.fit_resample(x_train_70, y_train_70)

# Check class distribution after SMOTE
print("After SMOTE with 80, 20 ratio train and test data:", dict(pd.Series(y_train).value_counts()))
print("After SMOTE with 70, 30 ratio train and test data:", dict(pd.Series(y_train_70).value_counts()))

Hyperparameter tuning for Decision Tree

In[470]:
# Hyperparameter tuning for Decision Tree
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

param_grid = {
    "max_depth": [3, 5, 10, None],
    "min_samples_split": [2, 5, 10],
    "min_samples_leaf": [1, 2, 4],
    "class_weight": ["balanced"],
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42), param_grid, scoring="recall", cv=5, n_jobs=-1)
grid_search.fit(x_dt_train, y_dt_train)

# Best parameters and retraining best model
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
best_tree_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(**best_params, random_state=42)
best_tree_model.fit(x_dt_train, y_dt_train)

y_pred_best_tree = best_tree_model.predict(x_dt_test)
best_tree_report = classification_report(y_dt_test, y_pred_best_tree)

# Print model performance
print("Best Decision Tree Parameters:", best_params)
print("Decision Tree Report (After Tuning):\n", best_tree_report)

Comparing Models with more Performance Evaluation Metrics

Considering the below metrics for comparing and evaluating the models

  • Accuracy (better prediction scores)
  • F1 score
  • Precision
  • Recall
  • True Positive Rate (TPR) = Recall
  • False Positive Rate (FPR)
  • True Negative Rate (TNR) = Specificity
  • False Negative Rate (FNR)
  • ROC AUC Score
  • Adjusted R (for completeness)
In[481]:
from sklearn.metrics import (accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, confusion_matrix, roc_curve, auc, roc_auc_score, r2_score)
# Determining Performance Evaluation Metrics
def compute_metrics(y_t, y_p, y_prob):
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_t, y_p).ravel()

    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_t, y_p)
    precision = precision_score(y_t, y_p)
    recall = recall_score(y_t, y_p)
    f1 = f1_score(y_t, y_p)

    # True Positive Rate (TPR) = Recall
    tpr = recall
    # False Positive Rate (FPR)
    fpr = fp / (fp + tn)
    # True Negative Rate (TNR) = Specificity
    tnr = tn / (tn + fp)
    # False Negative Rate (FNR)
    fnr = fn / (fn + tp)
    # ROC AUC Score
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_t, y_prob)
    # Adjusted R (for completeness)
    r2 = r2_score(y_t, y_p)

    return [accuracy, precision, recall, f1, tpr, fpr, tnr, fnr, roc_auc, r2]

# Create DataFrame for comparison
metrics = ["Accuracy", "Precision", "Recall (TPR)", "F1-Score", "TPR", "FPR", "TNR", "FNR", "ROC AUC", "Adjusted R"]
log_metrics = compute_metrics(y_test, y_predict_test, classifier.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1])
tree_metrics = compute_metrics(y_dt_test, y_dt_predict_test, dt.predict_proba(x_dt_test)[:, 1])
rf_metrics = compute_metrics(y_test, rf_predictions, rf_model.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1])
ada_metrics = compute_metrics(y_test, ada_predictions, ada_model.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1])
knn_metrics = compute_metrics(y_test, knn_predictions, knn_model.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1])

df_metrics = pd.DataFrame({"Metric": metrics,
                           "Logistic Regression": log_metrics,
                           "Decision Tree": tree_metrics,
                           "Random Forest": rf_metrics,
                           "AdaBoost": ada_metrics,
                           "KNN": knn_metrics
                           })

# Display Results
print(df_metrics)

Analyzing the model performances

Based on the evaluation metrics and ROC curve, Random Forest appears to be the best model among all the trained models. Here are the reasons in chosing Random Forest model:

  1. Highest ROC AUC (0.9966):
  • The closer the AUC is to 1, the better the model at distinguishing between classes. Random Forest and AdaBoost have the highest AUC values, but Random Forest has slightly better recall-precision balance.
  1. Perfect Recall (1.0000):
  • Random Forest correctly classifies all positive cases, which is crucial in scenarios where missing a positive instance is costly.
  1. High Accuracy (0.9800):
  • It performs well in overall classification.
  1. Balanced Precision and Recall:
  • Unlike Logistic Regression (which has low precision) or Decision Tree (which sacrifices recall slightly), Random Forest maintains a strong balance.
  1. Low False Positive Rate (FPR = 0.0212):
  • It minimizes misclassifications of negative instances, improving reliability.

While AdaBoost also has strong performance, its precision (0.6875) is lower than Random Forest's (0.7333), indicating that it misclassifies more negative instances as positives.

Thus, Random Forest is the best model due to its high accuracy, near-perfect recall, strong precision, and an excellent AUC score.
